To read a line of text from a file in C, you can implement a function like this:

```c
char *getLine(FILE *f) {
    char *line = NULL;
    size_t bufsize = 0;
    ssize_t linelen = getline(&line, &bufsize, f);
    if (linelen == -1) {
        free(line);  // Free memory allocated by getline
        return NULL; // Return NULL if there was an error or end of file
    }
    if (line[linelen - 1] == '\n') {
        line[linelen - 1] = '\0';  // Remove newline character if present
    }
    return line;
}
```

This function uses `getline()` to dynamically allocate memory for the line read from the file. It automatically adjusts the size of the buffer (`line`) based on the length of the line read. It returns `NULL` if it encounters an error or reaches the end of the file. Make sure to include `<stdio.h>` and `<stdlib.h>` headers for this function to work.

